Mexican Stocks: America Movil, Axtel, Comercial Mexicana, Gruma

-- B y   L e o n   L a z a r o f f   a n d   J o n a t h a n   J .   L e v i n
-- 
2011-03-28T21:50:07Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-28/mexican-stocks-america-movil-axtel-comercial-mexicana-gruma.html
The following companies had unusual
price changes in  Mexico  trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of 4:06 p.m. New York time.  The IPC index was little changed at 36,767.86.  America Movil  SAB (AMXL MM), the wireless carrier
controlled by billionaire  Carlos Slim , rose 0.2 percent to 33.80
pesos. Banco Santander SA raised its recommendation on the stock
to “buy” from “hold,” citing its “underperformance” and an
improved foreign-exchange outlook.  Axtel SAB (AXTELCPO MM) slipped 0.3 percent to 6.72 pesos.
Mexico’s second-largest landline phone company filed complaints
against Telefonos de Mexico SAB (TELMEXL MM) and Telcel with
telecommunications regulator for allegedly violating competition
laws. The complaints are in addition to those Axtel filed
earlier with the regulator, the company said in a statement.  Controladora Comercial Mexicana SAB (COMERUBC MM), the
Mexican supermarket operator, rose 2.5 percent to 19.08 pesos
after a report showed Mexico’s economy grew 5.85 percent in
January from a year earlier. Economists expected economic
activity, as measured by the global economic indicator, to rise
5.6 percent, according to the median estimate of 11 analysts
surveyed by Bloomberg.  Gruma SAB (GRUMAB MM), Mexico’s largest maker of corn flour
for tortillas, advanced 1.2 percent to 24.61 pesos. Gruma’s debt
rating was raised to BB- from B+ at  Standard & Poor’s .  To contact the reporters on this story:
